# Testing Standards

## Required Files per Component

Every component in `packages/ui` requires three test files:

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `Component.test.tsx` | Unit + interaction tests |
| `Component.a11y.test.tsx` | Accessibility violations (zero tolerance) |
| `Component.stories.tsx` | Storybook documentation |

## Unit Test Checklist

```tsx
describe('Button', () => {
  it('renders children')                    // ✓ renders
  it('applies correct variant class')       // ✓ prop → class
  it('fires onClick')                       // ✓ event
  it('does not fire onClick when disabled') // ✓ disabled state
  it('shows spinner when loading')          // ✓ loading state
  it('forwards ref')                        // ✓ ref forwarding
});
```

## Accessibility Test Template

```tsx
import { render } from '@testing-library/react';
import { axe } from '../../test-setup';

it('has no accessibility violations', async () => {
  const { container } = render(<MyComponent />);
  expect(await axe(container)).toHaveNoViolations();
});
```

## No Snapshots

Do NOT use `toMatchSnapshot()` — it masks regressions and breaks across environments.

## Query Priority (RTL)

Prefer queries in this order (most accessible → least):
1. `getByRole` — mimics how assistive tech finds elements
2. `getByLabelText` — for form fields
3. `getByText` — for visible text
4. `getByTestId` — last resort, requires `data-testid` prop

## Do Not Test Implementation Details

```tsx
// ❌ BAD — testing internal state
expect(component.state.isOpen).toBe(true);

// ✅ GOOD — testing user-visible behavior
expect(screen.getByRole('dialog')).toBeInTheDocument();
```
